<h2 id="the-patriarchy">The Patriarchy</h2>

<p>I feel the need to speak to this topic. For me, it‚Äôs a case of social MPP. There‚Äôs plenty of Post Modernism that might agree, that much if not all of our Social Construct is some kind of power game.</p>

<p>‚ÄúGuilty‚Äù I would say on the Dock, were I on trial for being part of a Patriarchal Hierarchy.</p>

<p>Giving up as much Power as I can and losing interest in Winning is the only response I have so far - before Impermanence takes me out of The Game. I am grateful for that. I wouldn‚Äôt choose a human nature that is so drawn to power.</p>

<h1 id="lucky-day">Lucky Day</h1>

<p>In summary‚Ä¶ I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôll ever be a Gamer. Sure, I‚Äôve been addicted to Adrenaline. I‚Äôve felt conflicted by younger folks feeling the need for a $3000 graphics card when the have other debts. I‚Äôm embarrassed to admit that I‚Äôve sometimes thought of Gamers as Losers. I apologise. I know that was unkind. It‚Äôs a way to some of that juice that our MPP places in us.</p>

<p>Calling somebody a Winner or Loser is often much harsher than Discernment.</p>

<p>I‚Äôve found myself in a place where Mining Magnates and Politicians that speak only of Growth (as a way to get re-elected) are people who Tom Waits‚Äô Dad described as:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Now when I was a boy<br />
  My daddy sat me on his knee<br />
  And he told me<br />
  He told me many things<br />
  And he said sone<br />
  There‚Äôs a lot of things in this world<br />
  ‚Äî<strong>You‚Äôre gonna have no use for</strong>‚Äî-<br />
  And when you get blue<br />
  And you‚Äôve lost all your dreams<br />
  There‚Äôs nothin‚Äô like a campfire<br />
  And a can of beans</p>
</blockquote>

<p>That‚Äôs right. I‚Äôve got No Use For Winning. Sorry, but it‚Äôll be a boring chess game.</p>

<p>If you‚Äôve seen anything like what I‚Äôve seen, you would know that Luck plays a significant role in our lives.</p>

<p>We were born in the 20th and 21st century. Some parts of that experience might be Lucky.</p>

<p>In fact, we are leaves in the stream more than Edmund Burke‚Äôs <a href="https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-edmund-burke-quote-idUSL1N2PG1EY">for good men to do nothing</a> heros.</p>

<p>We might have a sense of Meaning and might need to Win a few rounds before we get bored.</p>

<p>For me, I sense that anything good or meaningful that happened to me was a kind of happy accident.</p>

<p>And no, I‚Äôm not concerned that in certain ways Nihilism kind of resembles Impermanence.</p>

<p>Maybe a peaceful consciousness is much more Subtractive than a post modern world‚Äôs obsession with Appearances and Power will allow. Fortunately, that condition is Impermanent.</p>

<p>Have a <a href="https://youtu.be/pRwrMxzOV4g">Lucky Day</a>.</p>

<p>If you read till the very end, thank you. You might be interested in <a href="https://prajnaonline.org/video/embracing-the-truth-of-impermanence">this</a>.</p>
